   =20
      ARK
   =20
 =20
One thing that I  like to  say around here is that=C2=A0the primary job of =
a hedge fund manager is not picking stocks that go up, but rather continuin=
g to manage a hedge fund. If you lose a bunch of investor money one year an=
d the investors don=E2=80=99t take the rest of the money back =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0due to your personal charm or a reassuring previous history of performan=
ce or a=C2=A0compelling turnaround thesis or contractual lockups =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0then you had a pretty good year.This is much=C2=A0more=C2=A0true of a=
 mutual fund manager, or an exchange-traded fund manager, just due to the c=
ompensation scheme. If you run a hedge fund you charge fees of something li=
ke 2% of=C2=A0assets under management and 20% of profits; if you lose money=
 then your fees are not what you hoped for. If you run a mutual fund or ETF=
 you collect something like 0.5% of assets under management, and you genera=
lly don=E2=80=99t get a performance fee. Compensation-wise, the whole game =
is gathering lots of assets and keeping them them. Of course performance is=
 helpful in gathering assets, and of course losing money reduces your asset=
s and thus your fees. But good performance is not the only way to gather as=
sets, or to keep them.Here=E2=80=99s a story about ARK Investment Managemen=
t and its celebrity founder and manager Cathie Wood that contains an incred=
ible accolade (emphasis added):After a stellar 2020 in which it outshone ju=
st about everyone on Wall Street, ARK=E2=80=99s had a brutal 12 months. Its=
 flagship fund, the ARK Innovation ETF, has plunged more than 45% because o=
f its big bets on speculative technology-related companies. The S&P 500 ind=
ex has returned about 20% over the same period. Manager and ARK founder Cat=
hie Wood is perhaps best known for her huge commitment to Tesla Inc., and t=
hat stock is still positive compared with a year ago. But other top holding=
s including streaming device maker Roku, crypto exchange Coinbase Global, a=
nd virtual health-care provider Teladoc Health have tumbled.Say what you wi=
ll about Wood=E2=80=94and in online forums, on message boards, and across s=
ocial media, they pretty much say it all=E2=80=94few money managers have ev=
er lost as much cash yet kept so many investors. Although the Innovation fu=
nd=E2=80=99s assets had dropped by more than $15 billion from their peak in=
 February 2021 through to the end of January, the largest portion of that r=
eflects the declining value of its holdings. Less than 10% stemmed from inv=
estor withdrawals, and the fund ended the month with $13 billion in assets.=
 With a day=E2=80=99s worth of flow data in January still to come, the ETF =
had posted net inflows in 2022, even as it slumped about 20%.=E2=80=9CShe l=
ost so much cash but kept so many investors=E2=80=9D is perhaps not the nic=
est thing you can say about a=C2=A0stock-picker, but it is=C2=A0the very ni=
cest thing you could possibly say about a fund manager. Anyone can attract =
investors by making a lot of money for them; keeping investors after losing=
 a lot of money for them is the real skill. It is not too hard to explain h=
ow she has done it =E2=80=94=C2=A0a strong personal brand in an increasingl=
y dull industry, strongly held and intuitive arguments for why her thesis i=
s still right, a history of past performance =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that doesn=
=E2=80=99t make it easy to replicate.=C2=A0Also I will say that in a world =
of meme stocks it sort of makes sense that an investment manager who=E2=80=
=99s down 45% would still be a huge draw. The whole story of the 2020s stoc=
k market is that it=E2=80=99s not about fundamentals anymore; why shouldn=
=E2=80=99t the ETF market work the same way?
 =20
   =20
      Google split
   =20
 =20
I wrote=C2=A0yesterday about Alphabet Inc.=E2=80=99s stock split, which I c=
haracterized as a weird aesthetic appeal to retail investors who want to ow=
n a whole share of Google even though 0.1 shares is about 0.1 times as good=
. A couple of people pointed out that there are in fact practical benefits =
to having a low nominal stock price. For instance, while many U.S. retail b=
rokers are cool with fractional shares, it is perhaps easier to give employ=
ees share-based compensation in whole shares, and so a lower nominal stock =
price helps.Another big one is listed options, which ordinarily come in con=
tracts covering 100 shares. Byrne Hobart notes:But there's another constitu=
ency that matters: degenerate gamblers who trade options! A single at-the-m=
oney call contract for March covers 100 shares of Alphabet with a notional =
value of $296,000, requires a $12,000 cash outlay right now. =E2=80=A6 The =
average Robinhood account has $4,317, which keeps options on high-priced st=
ocks far out of reach. A split makes it easier for Robinhood customers to s=
peculate in options, and options-driven speculation is still growing ($, FT=
), and has an outsized impact given that options traders must buy the under=
lying when the stock goes up, while retail options traders have a tendency =
to respond to gains by buying more options.=C2=A0Two years ago if you had a=
sked me =E2=80=9Cdo trillion-dollar companies=C2=A0make corporate finance d=
ecisions to appeal to retail options traders=E2=80=9D I would have been ver=
y confused but now, I mean, who else would you make corporate finance decis=
ions for?We have  talked before about Cboe Global Markets Inc.=E2=80=99s =
=E2=80=9CNanos=E2=80=9D index options, which are scheduled to launch this y=
ear and will give retail traders a way to gamble cheaply on the S&P 500. I =
tell you what, whoever launches single-share single-stock options is going =
to make a fortune.
 =20
   =20
      Gotcha!
   =20
 =20
We have talked recently about  two  lawsuits over=C2=A0Elon Musk=E2=80=99s =
2018 tweet saying =E2=80=9CAm considering taking Tesla private at $420. Fun=
ding secured.=E2=80=9D In one lawsuit, JPMorgan Chase & Co. has sued Tesla =
Inc. claiming that this tweet constituted a formal announcement by Tesla th=
at it intended to enter into a merger agreement, which would entitle JPMorg=
an to a nine-digit payout under some Tesla warrants that it owned. In the o=
ther lawsuit, some Tesla shareholders have sued Musk, claiming that this tw=
eet constituted securities fraud because Musk was never really going to tak=
e Tesla private.A couple of readers emailed me yesterday to say: Wait, if M=
usk wins one case, doesn=E2=80=99t he lose the other? Either the tweet was =
serious or it wasn=E2=80=99t. If it was serious, then it was a merger annou=
ncement that triggered an adjustment to JPMorgan=E2=80=99s warrants; if it =
wasn=E2=80=99t serious it was fraud.I do love this argument and so I am pas=
sing it along to you, but I do not think it is actually correct. Tesla=E2=
=80=99s counterargument to JPMorgan is not actually =E2=80=9Ccome on he was=
 kidding=E2=80=9D; it is that =E2=80=9CMr. Musk=E2=80=99s personal consider=
ation of a possible transaction to take Tesla private was not tantamount to=
 a buyout announcement by the company.=E2=80=9D He really was =E2=80=9Ccons=
idering taking Tesla private,=E2=80=9D maybe he even had funding secured wh=
y not, but that doesn=E2=80=99t trigger the merger provisions of the warran=
ts because Tesla had not accepted a deal.[1]Similarly Musk=E2=80=99s counte=
rargument to the shareholder plaintiffs is not =E2=80=9Cactually I really w=
as going to take Tesla private,=E2=80=9D it=E2=80=99s that he was actually=
=C2=A0considering=C2=A0it, and that he actually=C2=A0had funding lined up.[=
2] It is=C2=A0weird=C2=A0for a corporate chief executive officer to announc=
e that he is=C2=A0pondering=C2=A0a going-private transaction; normally you =
wait until the deal is pretty baked before doing a thing like that. But it =
is not, in itself, fraud, and if the literal words that Musk wrote were tru=
e then that could be not-fraud but also not-a-merger.
 =20
   =20
      You can=E2=80=99t fondle the cube
   =20
 =20
Sure whatever:This morning, joggers in New York=E2=80=99s Central Park may =
have come across a curious, rather illustrious sight. A cube composed of 18=
6 kilograms of pure 24-karat gold, conceived by the German artist Niclas Ca=
stello who has billed it as a conceptual =E2=80=9Csocle du monde=E2=80=9D (=
base of the world) sculpture for our time, was wheeled out to the Naumburg =
Bandshell this morning at around 5 a.m.=C2=A0Although the work is not for s=
ale, according to the artist=E2=80=99s team, based on the current price of =
gold at $1,788 per ounce, its material worth is around $11.7 million. Flank=
ed by a heavy security detail, the 410-pound work is set to be displayed in=
 the park until the day=E2=80=99s end.Is there an accompanying non-fungible=
 token? I can=E2=80=99t believe you would even ask that.=E2=80=9CThe cube c=
an be seen as a sort of communiqu=C3=A9 between an emerging 21st-century cu=
ltural ecosystem based on crypto and the ancient world where gold reigned s=
upreme,=E2=80=9D says the Viennese gallerist Lisa Kandlhofer, who was in Ne=
w York for the artwork=E2=80=99s launch.Disappointingly the cube is hollow?=
 And comes up to your knee?[3] And here=E2=80=99s some more art guff:In a m=
essage sent this morning to Artnet News, Castello called the work =E2=80=9C=
a conceptual work of art in all its facets.=E2=80=9D He said the idea was t=
o =E2=80=9Ccreate something that is beyond our world=E2=80=94that is intang=
ible.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Is it intangible? No, in the sense that a cube of gold =
is a pretty literal solid physical object that is worth a lot of money just=
 in materials. Yes, in the sense that the security guards will not let you =
touch it.Elsewhere in =E2=80=A6=C2=A0art news? =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9CSoth=
eby=E2=80=99s Is Selling an Immense Black Diamond It Claims Came From Outer=
 Space.=E2=80=9D
 =20
